Standalone HTML/JS visualizer for browsing the compiled steno stroke tree; fetches `../out/viz-data.json` (must already exist â€” no server-side generation here) and renders it as a drill-down category â†’ stroke-choice â†’ preview UI with an on-screen steno keyboard diagram per sub-stroke. Must be served over `http://`, not opened as `file://`, since `fetch` requires it; on load failure it shows an inline error telling the user to run `target/debug/viz-data` first.

Key coupling: `LEFT_ORDER`/`MID_ORDER`/`RIGHT_ORDER` and `parseStroke` duplicate the canonical bank layout and parsing logic from `crates/steno/src/stroke/keys.rs` (`LEFT_ORDER`/`MID_ORDER`/`RIGHT_ORDER`, `parse_stroke`) â€” if that Rust layout changes, this JS copy must change too. `parseStroke` is intentionally lenient (no error path) because it only ever receives already-validated canonical strings from `viz-data.json`. The physical keyboard grid (`TOP_ROW`/`BOTTOM_ROW`/`VOWEL_ROW`) encodes the specific staggered two-row + split-star layout of a real steno keyboard, including that the same letter (e.g. `T`, `R`, `P`) appears in both a left-bank and right-bank position depending on column.

Expects `viz-data.json` to have shape `{ categories: [{label, roots}], nodes: { [key]: {axis, children, terminal, description, multiLine, oneLiner, oneLinerRoot} } }`. Axis nodes resolve via `resolve()` to their currently-selected option's node â€” an axis node's own key is never a real stroke and is never itself shown as a preview.

Non-obvious behavior worth knowing when editing:
- `path` only ever stores explicitly-clicked keys; singleton children (`isSingleton`) are auto-chained during `buildRows()` and never appear in `path`. If the tree shape changes upstream (e.g. an axis selection changes what's reachable), `buildRows()` self-heals by truncating `path` in place rather than erroring.
- `oneLinerActive` is a single global toggle, not per-node, matching the real constraint that multi-line vs. one-liner is chosen per whole construct, never per intermediate stroke (mirrors `lineflag.rs`).
- `currentOneLinerRoot` is recomputed once per `render()` from whichever row's node carries `oneLinerRoot`, then spliced into `displayKey()`'s output to show the augmented first stroke segment when one-liner mode is active.
- Root-level chips and each row's trailing children chips are always rendered (not conditionally hidden once picked), so any prior choice in the chain remains changeable by clicking a different chip â€” clicking truncates `path` to that row's index and appends the new key.
- `variantKeyFor` prefers the global `oneLinerActive` choice only when a node has both variants populated; falls back to whichever single variant exists otherwise.